<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="547" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,690,1472]" pageId="5" pageNumber="547">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,465,1086,1112]" pageId="5" pageNumber="547">Differential diagnosis:</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bezerra &amp; Pape &amp; Hauquier &amp; Vanreusel" authorityYear="2021" box="[473,590,1086,1112]" class="Chromadorea" family="Meyliidae" genus="Erebussau" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Desmoscolecida" pageId="5" pageNumber="547" phylum="Nematoda" rank="genus" status="nom. nov.">
<emphasis box="[473,590,1086,1112]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="547">Erebussau</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[599,716,1086,1112]" pageId="5" pageNumber="547">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[599,716,1086,1112]" pageId="5" pageNumber="547">nom. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
has a unique appearance when compared with the other genera of the family 
<taxonomicName authorityName="De Coninck" authorityYear="1965" box="[303,420,1122,1148]" class="Chromadorea" family="Meyliidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Desmoscolecida" pageId="5" pageNumber="547" phylum="Nematoda" rank="family">Meyliidae</taxonomicName>
. It has a distinct body annulation at the anterior and posterior end, without lateral field differentiation as found in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Decraemer &amp; Jensen" authorityYear="1982" box="[419,559,1158,1184]" class="Chromadorea" family="Meyliidae" genus="Noffsingeria" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Desmoscolecida" pageId="5" pageNumber="547" phylum="Nematoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[419,559,1158,1184]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="547">Noffsingeria</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The peculiar offset cephalic region of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bezerra &amp; Pape &amp; Hauquier &amp; Vanreusel" authorityYear="2021" box="[1002,1119,1158,1184]" class="Chromadorea" family="Meyliidae" genus="Erebussau" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Desmoscolecida" pageId="5" pageNumber="547" phylum="Nematoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1002,1119,1158,1184]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="547">Erebussau</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is unique among the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="De Coninck" authorityYear="1965" class="Chromadorea" family="Meyliidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Desmoscolecida" pageId="5" pageNumber="547" phylum="Nematoda" rank="family">Meyliidae</taxonomicName>
. Pigment spots were not described so far for 
<taxonomicName authorityName="De Coninck" authorityYear="1965" box="[701,815,1194,1220]" class="Chromadorea" family="Meyliidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Desmoscolecida" pageId="5" pageNumber="547" phylum="Nematoda" rank="family">Meyliidae</taxonomicName>
but they are clearly seen in 
<emphasis box="[1127,1252,1194,1220]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="547">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bezerra &amp; Pape &amp; Hauquier &amp; Vanreusel" authorityYear="2021" box="[1127,1248,1194,1220]" class="Chromadorea" family="Meyliidae" genus="Erebussau" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Desmoscolecida" pageId="5" pageNumber="547" phylum="Nematoda" rank="genus">Erebussau</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
The presence of phasmata-like structures are also described for the first time within the family 
<taxonomicName authorityName="De Coninck" authorityYear="1965" box="[1028,1145,1230,1256]" class="Chromadorea" family="Meyliidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Desmoscolecida" pageId="5" pageNumber="547" phylum="Nematoda" rank="family">Meyliidae</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="547" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,690,1472]" pageId="5" pageNumber="547">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,338,1266,1292]" pageId="5" pageNumber="547">Etymology:</emphasis>
The name is a combination of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Latreille" authorityYear="1810" box="[700,778,1266,1292]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Erebus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="547" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Erebus</taxonomicName>
(lat.) underworld, referring to the deep-sea habitat of the specimens; and an honor to Dr. Christian Bussau, who first described the genus giving the previous name, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Latreille" authorityYear="1810" box="[1344,1422,1302,1328]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Erebus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="547" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1344,1422,1302,1328]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="547">Erebus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
